text: I first discovered Battle Angel Alita when I was 14 years old. I was at a comic shop and found the first issue (VIZ Comics version) in a box marked "imports". I had never seen manga or even knew that the Japanese had their own style of comics. I was completely ignorant to that fact, and this new comic experience was an eye opener for me to say the least. I had never seen visuals like the ones contained in those comics. Needless to say I was completely and utterly hooked from the moment I saw it. I first heard about James Cameron acquiring the rights to Battle Angel Alita when I turned 16 from a now defunct website called "The Upcoming Movie List". I'm 36 now. 20 years I've waited for this to happen and I cannot even begin to tell you the surprise and excitement I felt when watching the first trailer.   For me this is a childhood dream made real in the best possible way. The visuals are faithful, the characterizations are accurate and they're throwing SO MUCH MONEY AT IT.  I'm happy to say the least.

text: I suppose Physics isn't a thing in this Universe then. as for all her speed she still can only put a certain amount of strength into her blows by virtue of being so light. So this isn't actually Sci Fi at all it's Science Fantasy.  They might have been better to bare that mind when making this to show she fineses her victories. Other wise it's a bit to much like expecting a 7 year old child to realistically beat up a pro wrestler.   The CGI flip flops a bit to close to uncanny valley at times too. so much so that (like Valarian) it looks like a cartoon with live action element and so has more in common with Detective Pikachu or who framed roger rabbit.   That said - what there is - seems stronger than the visual catastrophe of Valarian or Ready Player One. Though I expect the battle scenes will be a CGI Sh**show where you can't tell what is going on at any point. I may watch it though But I'm expecting "Meh" not 'great'. (if because Hollywood has 'Meh' as a it's default setting).   Just try not to make a movie as banal as Solo : A Star Wars story or disjointed as Pacific Rim's sequel - that is at least a good place to start. But i'm pretty bored with CGI now - so that is a point against it.

text: All this dialogue about how she's seemingly a teenage girl, but NOBODY would think that about her with those jumbo sized, plush animal eyes. Since she's designed to appear human on the surface, then why Roger Rabbit the first thing you look at? Ed Skrein is seen sporting a full Terminator body here, but he STILL appears to be a human character that has gone overboard with augmentations - because he retains his normal, human face. Alita's eyes make no sense within the world of the film, but the filmmakers are selling it hard with cringy lines like "you are the most human person I have ever met" ...I'll be watching this purely for the cyberpunk production design.

But it is plain to see as with the previous trailers that the story, and even the characters that Yukito Kishiro had created seems to have been changed quite substantially, and what only remains may be a shadow of his original work. Much of the OAV seems to be main inspiration for this movie. And again delayed till February!  I hope this is not going to be another repeat of Ghost in the shell where all of the hollywood changes diminished Shirow's Manga and vision. All I can do is wait and hope that when I finally get to see this movie, one I have since reading the graphic novels wanted to see on the big screen, it is true to the source and not too far removed from it to be considered as another failure of adapting a  popular, significant, and iconic Japanese Manga to the big screen.

text: It looks okay, but not really distinct. Imo the dystopian and bleak theme of the manga as well as the extremely kinetic fight scenes should have led to a more distinct visual style than "Look, we made her eyes weird". The issue is not that they eyes are manga style but the reason why? It has no reason to be that way based on her character and given the visuals of the movie it has no reason to be there based on the style of the movie.  I just can hope this will be mediocre when imo the source material would have deserved a "Mad Max: Fury Road" level of action movie in terms of visuals and pace and quite easily a R rating given the world it plays in,

I believe to a degree it costed a very well recieved Bumblebee (the best reviewed Transformers film) from having greater financial success, and the same could have happened to Alita. text: Many reviewers criticise the movie (among some other things) because of the felt not closed story. It is important to know, that the source material contains of a lot more story, than the movie can deliver in only 2 hours. There are (more or less) 3 books out of 9 (without the OVA) packed into the movie. So it is clear, that there may be a unsatisfiying ending for all people who don`t know the source material. BUT, from what I`ve seen and heard so far, it seems to be everything I`ve wished to see for a lot of years while waiting for this movie. Even if you haven`t read the manga, I can assure you (so far) it will be worth your time. And may it be only for the visuells - but the real greatness of the story lies in the philosophical question of what it means to be human. MUST SEE

I had no prior knowledge of this movie or the actors or designers or producers involved. This is my unbiased opinion when I say I deeply dislike your protagonist. I love the sci-fi genre, especially when it comes to that cyberpunk/Neo-Tokyo type stuff. I would consider seeing this movie if it weren‚Äôt for the protagonist. text: It really annoys me when contemporary, colloquial language is used in other centuries.  If one considers how teenagers in particular talked even 30 years ago compared to now they would be using different slang words and phrases.  This film is set 500 years in the future and yet people are using such expressions as "Awesome" and "that was intense"  and all manner of other contemporary speak.  This always happens and it spoils the movie for me.  The only one who got it right was Stanley Kubrick with A clockwork orange, although credit there would really go to the author of the book, Anthony Burgess.

text: Why is this movie being marketed so horribly? I had to actually look up the trailer first of all because the ones they paid for on YouTube ads are only ten seconds and don‚Äôt say anything at all. Also, this complete trailer seems like it‚Äôs spoiling so much of the story. She seems like a girl desperate to seem normal yet at the end of the trailer she‚Äôs already super confident in her abilities? What changed that? It doesn‚Äôt matter now does it? Also, we know the love interest, that they kiss and we know when they kiss. Completely spoils the romance. We know that she can kick ass and that she will kick ass. What SHOULD be revealed in the trailer actually IS NOT. Who is the antagonist and why is Alita a threat? What is the natural order of things in this distant future? Why should we care? This is looking to be a repeat of Disney‚Äôs Treasure Planet minus the fact that Alita isn‚Äôt being released during an extremely competitive month

text: Not a good film at all.  It was absolutely awful from start to finish... it picked up a rough 51% on metacritic and is currently at 60% on rotten tomatoes as of now, it's went up slightly but even still that's not positive really at all, and honestly I see why it got that. It had the potential to be amazing, alita was such a likable character and she wasn't annoying, there were also so many good actors. I feel like the only good thing that actually came out of this movie was the action and the overall CGI. It was sloppy, the plot was terrible and most of the scenes where just upright cringe. It could have been amazing, but it was terrible. I went to watch it with 7 people, and everyone felt the exact same way as me. I even heard someone mutter a 'Jesus that was awful' to their friend walking out haha. Sure, everyone has their opinions, but I am with the critics on this one... very dissapointed with it if I'm honest. Big let down.  Spoilers!!! Also, this film could have ended in like 7  different places, then ended where there shouldn't have been an ending. Why give the boyfriend, who by the way was very unlikable, 2 deaths in about 5 minutes. It could have been thought out so much better.

text: Ok, officially watched the special IMAX 3d fan event.  The verdict: from someone has digital copies of gunnm Alita, original motorball 3dcg avi,DVD ova's... everything but vol19 of LO, prequels, and Ashen: Mixed.  Got vol 1+2 on point. Vol.3+4 were intermixed into the first 2, effectively reversing some parts, but by reworking some sub-sub points/plots, they were able to intertwine them into the first 2 stories, and introduce some prequel materials as well.  So over all, descent.  "It's neither good nor bad" - Ido.  It will need more movies though.  It brought a tear to me eye when they did the motorball Damascus water slice near identically to the 3dcgi from 25 years ago. :)

text: Movie is AWESOME!!! Still, I can't help commenting about people complaining about Alita's character being CGI with big anime eyes. They should know that it is the best decision that the production team did for this movie. Why?  1. She is NOT NORMAL, so why must she look like a normal human being. Past anime-to-movie adaptations are disappointing because their actors do not look close enough to the manga/anime characters. They are just too normal for that role.  2. To pay homage to the source material. Alita's eyes were also pointed out in the manga. So if the creators promise to stay true to the manga, they definitely should show that through the heroine.  3. If you watch the movie, the anime eyes is a distinct feature of "her kind". Meaning it is to differentiate Alita and her kind from the human beings.  4. Necessary for future sequels. Alita should look young, doll-like, and vulnerable. This is why villains underestimate her. The movie alone is almost 3 yrs in the making. If there will be 3 or more sequels (I really wish there will be), that's a lot of years of filming and the lead actress should look the same within 10 yrs or more. Don't get me wrong, Rosa Salazar is beautiful and perfect for the role, but to achieve all of the characteristics I mentioned previously, CGI is the only way to go.  So if you want to watch it, just watch it, it will not disappoint. Most of the people who watched the movie love it and that should be enough proof that it's good. I wish those naysayers will stop saying things they know nothing of, like they know better than the author Yukito Kishiro who approves the movie, the production team and the anime/manga fans. Just enjoy the movie guys. ‚úåüòá ‚ù§‚ù§‚ù§üíØ
author: Eira Mesorina

text: Just returned from watching this in the theatre and I enjoyed it thoroughly! I don't have to talk about the visuals because everyone is, and the action sequences are top notch. I just felt like they spent too much time in the film exploring the world (which I loved, but could have been paced better) and left very little runtime to the actual plot. This made the plot rushed and character development for other supporting characters half-assed (like Chiren's change of heart, which gave me whiplash because she showed no indication of it at all until it actually happened). I thought they could've split this movie into 2 and paced it all out better, and give themselves more room to explore the unique world. May have been better to end the movie after the battle with Giwenska (sp?) and keep the audience in suspense to Alita's well-being till the next movie. Sincerely enjoyed it, but disappointed that the potential was wasted when they rushed through the plot. Unpopular opinion

text: To rate the quality of a movie, based on more then legendary original material, is similar to trying to explain and define quantum physics. How can one even try, if even the original material has countless diverse interpretations on its meaning and essence? In fact, I haven't yet had the pleasure to see for my self, but the indicators for highest quality movie making, at least by todays standards are not so bad for this release.   It is produced by renowned producers,  not only having produced some of the true classics of the scifi genre, but also having directed some of them. I personally never liked Avatar, but that is personal opinion, and far from objective. But Aliens is a classic at its own rights, not as good as Alien, but what is? But still a more than a decent follow up, 2010 can not tell the same story here, for instance.  Despite from that, we have producers here with a financial background suitable to pull a production as this of on their own, not having anyone pull the strings in the back, like some crazy german fond fed by chinese or russian, stupid rich no names.  And we see one of the finest directors of today, one of the few with the guts to deliver his beliefs in entirety having directed this movie.  And still, this will never reach the status of being a classic. But it will certainly be an enjoyable film, true as possible to what its makers understood of the original material.  I simply do not understand, why so many people love this, but hated the Ghost in the Shell movie.  Compared to some whatever, worse than 70s triple x movie everyone loved, like, in particular, Valerian, these both are great, worthy interpretations of the original.

text: jesus i can't understand why there's so many positive comments. THIS MOVIE WAS TERRIBLE. Here's a somewhat (at least I tried) unbiased review:  1) the only good part are the fight scenes, which I will be honest and say that they looked pretty sick  2) there was no backstory or context, which i suppose is fine if you know the comics/manga or whatever, but for me and my friend, we didn't have that background information, so everything was just confusing  3) the pacing was TERRIBLE. I'm not go into too many details because then it'd be spoilers, but everything was just confusing since the beginning. it got better for me as the movie progressed, but my friend HATED the movie  4) the acting was just plain awful. now before people rip me apart, i'm not going to straight up blame the actress because I don't know the actress who played alita, and i don't know if she's a good actor. I do know, however, that everything looked so fake on the screen it was downright laughable. her smile, her acting, everything about her was so stressed. There's this sad scene near the end of the movie (again not going to go into in because spoilers), but where you can tell it was supposed to be sad, the entire movie theater just burst into laughter. I am not even kidding, i could hear people laughing in the theater. It was just awful. there's zero connection to the characters, which is why you can't feel for them. i'm going to be very truthful and say that this movie had the potential to be a good movie despite all its other faults, but one of the main, MAIN reasons it was so terrible was because of the acting. i suppose it might have something to do with the cgi, because i watched a behind the scenes video and her acting looked pretty convincing then.  5) everything good about this movie is in the trailers. I must admit they made the trailers look AMAZING, which was why i was so excited to go see it in the theaters. but everything that's not in the trailers SUCK. they hyped this movie up too much, which makes it an even bigger disappointment when you actually watch it.  6) overall summary: it's not a bad movie to watch when you're EXTREMELY bored and have nothing else to do. the action scenes for one IS pretty lit. But it is definitely NOT something you would want to spend money for tickets. NOT WORTH IT.   no hating. just my opinion.

text: I came to the movie out of curiosity and because James Cameron has a good track record for movies with stunning visuals.  But I had never read any of the Manga stories.  Therefore I had no preconceived notions regarding the story line.  I was not disappointed with the movie and might even buy a copy once the initial DVD prices drop a bit.  But there was one serious problem with the theater where I saw it.  They had the Dolby sound turned way up and many times the floor shook like we were having an earthquake.  That was a bit unnerving.  Because I have issues with my vision (one cataract removed, other still in place), I cannot comfortably watch a 3D movie right now, but this one was clear enough for ordinary projection and I could imagine that seeing some of the combat in 3D would be awesome.  Not the best movie I've ever seen but DEFINITELY above average.

text: This film is absolutely unimaginable.¬†Alita is one of the best experiences I have ever had in my life. I haven't been this emotionally attached to the protagonist in any other movie I watched in the past. She is so badass and loveable, and her character design just adds to the tally. This movie gives you a whole new viewing experience with amazing never seen before fighting scenes and scenery. Trust me: I am the type of guy to get bored watching a movie for the second time, but with this, I can't wait to go and watch it again. I find it unbelievable that such a movie would be voted badly/average on rotten tomato's and Box Office, but I heard it's getting better and it is being released in the East and more countries worldwide. The producers are complete geniuses and the graphic designers and editors were phenomenal. If I could, I would donate millions to this movie so it could surmount its production cost as fast as possible. I think I speak for everyone when I say this: There MUST be a sequel. SEQUEL SEQUEL SEQUEL. Please, everyone do your part and rate this movie with high stars. Share with your friends, family, and even your dog because they will love it too. I spent way too much time writing this review now, but it just goes to show how unbelievable this film was. 10/10 from me¬†üëç

text: If you're a fan and/or read the manga, don't even bother watching it. If you haven't read the manga yet, go ahead and give it a watch. I guess, on its own, it's a great enough film. It definitely has more passion put into it than Dragon Ball Evolution. The action is the best part, I mean, it's all CGI, so..  But, I laugh at the fact that the director supposedly calls himself a fan, he butchered too much of the original and completely misses key points from it... They could potentially finish the story in a trilogy, since the original series IS a three-parter so far, but the way they set things up in this film will make that rather difficult. To the point that it isn't even Alita anymore. Like, the whole thing with Nova is just no. In all honesty, it's just an amalgamation of the original comic. Like, why bother make a live action film if you're going to mess with it? Just do it as is, obviously the original writer is much better than you are at telling THEIR story...

text: *Better than expected, actually.* After Ghost In the Shell I didn't have much hope for another US anime adaptation but this was a pleasant surprise. Close to the source material, good actors, good CGI.. especially the exteriors. The cyborgs were maybe a bit too cyborg-y at times. Would probably look better with more human parts. But overall I liked it, even though I'm not in the target audience which is probably young adults..  I hope we get a sequel! Would like to see what the floating city looks like, more flashbacks from Alita's past and more space battles. There's some real 26th century sci-fi potential here..

text: I didn't know anything about Alita from before. Just thought she looked really interesting on the poster at the cinema. Went to see it on the last day in 3D. It hit me like a train! I became addicted. Luckily for me, I work at the cinema, so I could see it many more times after it had expired. 9 more times to be exact. First time Wednesday then Saturday, Sunday, 2 times Monday, Tuesday, 2 times Wednesday and 2 times Thursday. The film will be removed from the system now. Sad times! I can't even begin to explain how much I love this movie! The film itself is awesome, but Alita is just... I don't know what to say. I know this is cringe, but I think I'm a little in love. I'm that kind of guy. I'm gonna buy this movie on dvd AND bluray. Gonna make my own archive of photos from my favourite moments. Can't wait to see it again! I really really want this to get a sequel! It has to! Right? We NEED to know more about Zalem and Nova. WHEN Alita becomes final champion she will go to Zalem, right? Need more answers.  Can't believe how much I have written now. I'm so lost. Need Alita to save me.  One more thing:  Two of my favourite moments are in the first fight scene. #1 is Alita's eyes after she beats the guy to death. When she stands back up. #2 is also Alita's eyes after Grewishka jumps down the hole. When she is standing on the edge looking for him.  Long story short, Alita: Battle Angel is an amazing movie! I would see it even more times if I could. Have to wait for the bluray now. (sobbs in the corner)

text: I loved that scene between Alita and Hugo. I guess a lot of people found it cringe-worthy but how else can they express how they feel about each other and make it so meaningful? It seems so weird to us because she's a cyborg but she has the thing that is the basis of our existence which is a human brain and emotions. And with her Berserker body, she could now feel more human than ever. This scene felt right to me. You could see how enamored she was with him when she first met him. It makes his loss that much more painful when she loses him. The scene near the end with the tear was pretty powerful. I hope she gets her revenge someday.
